Basic image exercises with matplotlib.¶

In [2]:
names = ["images/javier.png","images/rocio.png","images/pablo.png"]

for n in names:
    im = image.imread(n)
    print("Imagen:", n)
    print("Type:", im.dtype)
    print("Size:", im.shape)
    print("Mean:", np.mean(im))
    print("Max:", np.max(im))
    print("Min:", np.min(im))
    plt.imshow(im)
    plt.show()

Basic image exercises with PIL.¶

In [3]:
names = ["images/javier.png","images/rocio.png","images/pablo.png"]

for n in names:
    img= Image.open(n)
    print("Format:", img.format)
    print("Mode:", img.mode)
    print("Size:", img.size)
    img.show()
    print('Transposing')
    plt.imshow(img.transpose(Image.FLIP_TOP_BOTTOM))
    plt.show()
    print('Rotating 30º')
    plt.imshow(img.rotate(30))
    plt.show()
    print('Crop to (100,100) size')
    crop = img.crop((250, 250, 350, 350))
    print(crop.size)
    plt.imshow(crop)
    plt.show()
    print('Histogram')
    plt.plot(img.histogram())
    img.save(n+"saved", format="PNG")
    plt.show()

Transform numpy array to PIL image and vice versa¶

In [4]:
names = ["images/javier.png","images/rocio.png","images/pablo.png"]

for n in names:
    print(n)
    img = Image.open(n)
    imgNp= asarray(img) #PIL to Numpy
    print(type(imgNp))
    imgPIL = Image.fromarray(imgNp) #Numpy to PIL
    print(type(imgPIL))
    print('\n')
